    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1886-10-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1886-10-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="277"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d277">
                <head>No. 273.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Woodbury</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-10-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 15, 1886</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have your letter of the 12th instant,
                    accompanied by sundry affidavits, stating the deposit of $200 by the master of
                    the American fishing schooner Pearl Nelson, under the compulsion of the customs
                        <pb facs="0610" n="526" xml:id="pg_526"/> officers at the port of Arichat,
                    Cape Breton, the ground alleged for this action by the officials at Arichat
                    being the unlawful landing of the crew of the Pearl Nelson before reporting at
                    the custom-house.</p>
                <p>The case will be presented to the British minister at this capital, and
                    notification given to him that compensation will be demanded for violation of
                    the treaty privileges, should the British Government be found liable for breach
                    of international duty on examination of the law and facts.</p>
                <p>Your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>T. F. BAYARD.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
